2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="0" top="312" width="97">ABSTRACT</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="331" width="359">Bullying is a serious national health issue among adolescents.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="347" width="359">Social media oers a new opportunity to study bullying in</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="363" width="359">both physical and cyber worlds. Sentiment analysis has the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="378" width="359">potential to identify victims who pose high risk to them-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="394" width="359">selves or others, and to enhance the scientic understanding</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="410" width="359">of bullying overall. We identify seven emotions common in</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="426" width="359">bullying. While some of the emotions are well-studied be-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="441" width="359">fore, others are non-standard in the sentiment analysis lit-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="457" width="359">erature. We propose a fast training procedure to recognize</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="473" width="359">these emotions without explicitly producing a conventional</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="488" width="359">labeled training dataset. We apply our procedure to social</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="504" width="297">media posts on bullying and discuss our ndings.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="0" top="537" width="270">Categories and Subject Descriptors</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="556" width="359">H.2.8 [DATABASE MANAGEMENT]: Database Ap-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="572" width="359">plicationsData mining ; I.2.7 [ARTIFICIAL INTELLI-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="587" width="339">GENCE]: Natural Language ProcessingText analysis</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="0" top="620" width="114">General Terms</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="639" width="67">Algorithms</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="0" top="672" width="77">Keywords</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="691" width="296">sentiment analysis, bullying, social media mining</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="1" top="724" width="302">1.  INTRODUCTION TO BULLYING</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="743" width="359">Bullying, also called peer victimization, has been identied</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="759" width="359">as a serious national health concern among adolescents [39,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="775" width="359">38, 1]. One is being bullied or victimized when he or she</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="790" width="359">is exposed repeatedly over time to negative actions on the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="806" width="359">part of others [30]. Far-reaching and insidious sequelae of</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="822" width="359">bullying include intrapersonal problems [18, 17] and lethal</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="837" width="359">school violence in the most extreme cases [26]. Youth who</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="853" width="359">experience peer victimization report more symptoms of de-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="869" width="359">pression, anxiety, loneliness, and low self-worth compared to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="884" width="359">their nonvictimized counterparts [3, 4, 13, 15]. Bullying hap-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="900" width="359">pens traditionally in the physical world and, recently, online</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="916" width="359">as well; the latter is known as cyberbullying [7, 12, 42, 41].</text>
2 <text font="5" height="11" left="81" textpieces="0" top="963" width="359">Permission to make digital or hard copies of all or part of this work for</text>
2 <text font="5" height="11" left="81" textpieces="0" top="977" width="359">personal or classroom use is granted without fee provided that copies are not</text>
2 <text font="5" height="11" left="81" textpieces="0" top="990" width="359">made or distributed for prot or commercial advantage and that copies bear</text>
2 <text font="5" height="11" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1004" width="359">this notice and the full citation on the rst page. Copyrights for components</text>
2 <text font="5" height="11" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1017" width="359">of this work owned by others than ACM must be honored. Abstracting with</text>
2 <text font="5" height="11" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1031" width="359">credit is permitted. To copy otherwise, to republish, to post on servers or to</text>
2 <text font="5" height="11" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1044" width="317">redistribute to lists, requires prior specic permission and/or a fee.</text>
