2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="315" width="359">Bullying takes multiple forms, most noticeably face-to-face</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="331" width="359">physical (e.g., hitting), verbal (e.g., name-calling), and rela-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="346" width="359">tional (e.g., exclusion) [2, 23, 29]. Cyberbullying reects a</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="362" width="359">venue (other than face to face contact) through which ver-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="378" width="359">bal and relational forms can occur. Bullying usually starts</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="393" width="359">in primary school, peaks in middle school, and lasts well into</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="409" width="359">high school and beyond [27, 36, 9]. Across a national sam-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="425" width="359">ple of students in grades 4 through 12 in the United States,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="440" width="359">38% of students reported being bullied by others and 32%</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="456" width="176">reported bullying others [40].</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="488" width="359">Participants in a bullying episode take well-dened roles (see</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="503" width="359">Figure 1). The traditional roles include the bully (or bul-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="519" width="359">lies), the victims, bystanders (who saw the event but did not</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="535" width="359">intervene), defenders of the victim, assistants to the bully</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="550" width="359">(who did not initiate but went along with the bully), and</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="566" width="359">reinforcers (who did not directly join in with the bully but</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="582" width="359">encouraged the bully by laughing, for example) [34]. We</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="597" width="359">also dened two new roles that are common in social media:</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="613" width="359">reporter (may not be present during the episode, unlike a by-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="629" width="359">stander) and accuser (accusing someone as the bully) [43].</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="644" width="359">More than one person can have the same role in a bullying</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="660" width="48">episode.</text>
2 <text font="5" height="10" left="502" textpieces="0" top="797" width="44">reinforcer</text>
2 <text font="5" height="10" left="502" textpieces="0" top="713" width="43">bystander</text>
2 <text font="7" height="13" left="595" textpieces="1" top="795" width="106">bully       victim</text>
2 <text font="5" height="10" left="591" textpieces="2" top="713" width="215">assistant        defender            reporter</text>
2 <text font="7" height="13" left="767" textpieces="0" top="795" width="42">accuser</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="893" width="359">Figure 1: Participants role in a bullying episode</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="909" width="164">(Reproduced from [43])</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="941" width="359">Bullying has been studied from at least two angles. The</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="957" width="359">social science study of bullying has a long history but is lim-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="972" width="359">ited by small sample size and time-consuming data collec-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="988" width="359">tion [28]. The computer science study of bullying is emerg-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1004" width="359">ing with promising results [43, 22, 10, 33, 20, 5, 21]. The</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1020" width="359">latter has a distinct focus on bullying in social media, where</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1035" width="359">participants of a bullying episode post their bullying experi-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1051" width="359">ences. Such posts, called bullying traces, include but far</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1067" width="359">exceed incidences of cyberbullying. In our previous work,</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
