2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="86" width="359">we showed how computational techniques can help to an-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="102" width="359">swer several scientic questions by mining bullying traces in</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="118" width="359">Twitter [43]. However, to our knowledge emotions in bully-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="133" width="359">ing traces have not received wide attention from the research</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="149" width="359">community. It is the goal of the present paper to raise aware-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="165" width="359">ness of this fertile topic, and to provide initial results on the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="180" width="169">sentiment study of bullying.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="1" top="211" width="358">2.  EMOTIONS IN BULLYING TRACES AS</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="112" textpieces="0" top="232" width="346">IDENTIFIED BY OUR SENTIMENT CLAS-</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="112" textpieces="0" top="253" width="60">SIFIER</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="272" width="359">Sentiment analysis on bullying traces is of signicant impor-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="288" width="359">tance. Victims usually experience negative emotions such</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="303" width="359">as depression, anxiety and loneliness. In extreme cases such</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="319" width="338">emotions are more violent or even suicidal, for example,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="113" textpieces="0" top="356" width="293">Im tired of all this bullying. I could never stand</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="372" width="291">up for myself &amp; sometimes I just want to kill</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="388" width="49">myself.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="425" width="359">Detecting at-risk individuals via sentiment analysis enables</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="441" width="359">potential interventions. In addition, social scientists are in-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="456" width="359">terested in sentiment analysis on bullying traces to under-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="472" width="192">stand participants motivations.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="503" width="359">There are a wide range of emotions expressed in bullying</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="1" top="519" width="359">traces.  After manually inspecting a number of bullying</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="535" width="359">traces in Twitter, our domain experts identied seven most</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="550" width="113">common emotions:</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="588" width="343">1. Anger: He is always laughing at me because he is a</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="603" width="144">bully damnit! #Ashley</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="627" width="342">2. Embarrassment: @USER everyone is bullying me be-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="643" width="325">cause I couldnt nd the word peach in a crossword.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="659" width="57">Its 1am</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="1" top="683" width="343">3. Empathy: @USER Im sorry you get bullied.  Im</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="698" width="325">really surprised at how many people this has happened</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="714" width="111">to. #bulliesSuck </text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="738" width="343">4. Fear: i was being bullied and i didnt want to go to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="754" width="325">school really i would throw ts everymorning and i hope</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="769" width="129">that michel sees this</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="793" width="343">5. Pride: Everyone on this earth is a bully , except me .</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="809" width="184">Because Im perfect. #jillism</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="833" width="343">6. Relief: @USER I was rambling and then... I cried.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="849" width="325">Like, CRIED. He was touched! APC helped me thru</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="864" width="193">the teasing and bullying man...</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="888" width="342">7. Sadness: things were bad when I was younger I got</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="904" width="325">bullied so much because of my disabilites I dont want</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="920" width="251">the same thing happening to my brother.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="957" width="359">This list is by no means comprehensive. Other emotions or</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="972" width="359">mixtures of several basic emotions may also appear in bul-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="988" width="359">lying traces. These seven categories are the most common</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1004" width="359">ones based on our current study. Also note that due to the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1020" width="359">length limits (140 characters), an individual tweet may be</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="1" top="1035" width="358">only a sentence in a conversation thread.  Therefore, the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1051" width="359">majority of bullying traces in Twitter cannot be associated</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1067" width="138">with denite emotions.</text>
=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="475" textpieces="1" top="83" width="359">3.  A FAST MACHINE LEARNING PROCE-</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="507" textpieces="0" top="104" width="51">DURE</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="124" width="359">As shown above, some emotions involved in bullying traces</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="139" width="359">have not been well studied in sentiment analysis, for exam-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="155" width="359">ple, embarrassment and relief. To make the problem worse,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="171" width="359">manually labeling a large amount of training tweets is di-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="186" width="328">cult and time consuming even for our domain experts.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="218" width="359">Recognizing these challenges, we use a fast training proce-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="234" width="359">dure for sentiment analysis. Our goal is supervised learn-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="249" width="359">ing, specically classifying a tweet into one of the predened</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="265" width="359">emotion categories. However, we require no explicit labeled</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="281" width="359">training data on tweets. Instead, we will rely on distantly</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="296" width="359">labeled data (to be made clear next) that are much easier</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="312" width="359">to obtain. We point out upfront that it will be dicult to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="328" width="359">assess the accuracy of the resulting classier, since we do</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="343" width="359">not have an in-domain labeled dataset. However, our obser-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="359" width="359">vations point to a useful classier. Coupled with the ease of</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="375" width="359">training and its applicability to other emotions and domains,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="390" width="192">our procedure is still attractive.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="475" textpieces="1" top="427" width="225">3.1  Relations to Prior Work</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="446" width="359">Most sentiment analysis work focused on the overall polar-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="462" width="359">ity of a document: positive, negative or neutral [32, 24]. A</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="477" width="359">few work considered several basic emotions at a ner level</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="493" width="359">and created emotional lexicons for each category [37]. Re-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="509" width="359">cently, sentiment analysis on social media [44], especially</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="525" width="359">Twitter [31], has been receiving increasing attention. Cam-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="540" width="359">bria et al. [6] proposed a sentiment analysis approach to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="556" width="359">identify malicious posts from social media. Our domain of</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="572" width="359">bullying is fresh with very few existing resources. In addi-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="587" width="359">tion, although bullying traces are abundant, only a small</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="1" top="603" width="359">fraction of them are associated with strong emotions.  It</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="619" width="359">poses challenges to obtain enough training examples for all</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="634" width="359">the emotion categories, especially the rare and non-standard</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="650" width="30">ones.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="681" width="359">Our approach is inspired by the concept labeling work of</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="697" width="359">Chenthamarakshan et al. [8] to minimize the supervision ef-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="713" width="359">fort in constructing text classication models. In their sys-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="729" width="359">tem, instead of labeling a set of training examples experts</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="744" width="359">annotate how concepts are related to the target class. We</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="760" width="359">push this idea further where neither labeled examples nor</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="776" width="359">labeled concepts are necessary for building the emotion clas-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="791" width="38">siers.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="823" width="359">Our procedure consists of two steps. The rst step is in</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="838" width="359">the same spirit as the dictionary-based sentiment lexicon</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="854" width="359">generation method [16], which exploits synonym structure of</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="870" width="359">a dictionary to bootstrap the sentiment lexicon. Our second</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="885" width="359">step is similar to the idea of corpus-based sentiment lexicon</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="901" width="359">generation method [14, 19], which uses a domain corpus to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="917" width="359">extend sentiment lexicon by sentence structure or sentiment</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="933" width="359">consistency assumption. As tweets are very short  usually</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="948" width="359">a few sentences  the sentiment is usually consistent within</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="964" width="48">a tweet.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="475" textpieces="1" top="1000" width="170">3.2  Task Description</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1020" width="359">Following [43], we obtain bullying traces via Twitter stream-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1035" width="359">ing API such that: (i) each tweet contains at lease one the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1051" width="359">following keywords bully, bullied, bullying, and (ii) the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1067" width="359">tweet passes a bullying-or-not text classier. We want to rec-</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="86" width="359">ognize the emotion involved in each bullying trace identied</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="102" width="359">by this procedure. We dene 8 emotion classes: anger, em-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="118" width="359">barrassment, empathy, fear, pride, relief, sadness, and other.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="133" width="359">The last class captures bullying traces without obvious emo-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="149" width="359">tion or not one of the seven emotions. Thus, our task is to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="165" width="341">build an eight-class text classier with little supervision.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="1" top="201" width="147">3.3  Fast Learning</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="220" width="359">Our learning procedure includes four steps: (1) collecting</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="236" width="359">seed words, (2) collecting online documents, (3) creating fea-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="252" width="359">ture extractors, and (4) building a text classier. None of</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="268" width="265">the steps requires explicit labeling a corpus.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="299" width="359">Collecting Seed Words. We start by collecting seed words</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="1" top="315" width="358">Sewhich are related to each emotion e (except for the other</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="330" width="359">category). Lexicons exist for certain emotions such as anger</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="346" width="359">and sadness but not all [37]. As we want to handle the non-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="362" width="359">standard emotion categories, we create such lists from two</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="377" width="324">general resources which are available for all emotions:</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="421" width="341">1. Many websites provide synonym dictionary service.1</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="437" width="325">We look up the category name of emotion e such as</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="113" textpieces="0" top="453" width="256">anger and add all its synonyms to SSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="343" textpieces="1" top="458" width="31">e       .</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="482" width="343">2. We search for the category name of emotion e in Word-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="498" width="325">Net [25, 11], and add all words appearing in the synsets</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="514" width="48">to SW N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="142" textpieces="2" top="519" width="298">e      .    In addition, we also include all words in</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="530" width="325">synsets listed as their derivationally related form and</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="545" width="327">their similar to, full troponym or full hyponyms</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="561" width="325">sets depending on the part of speech (adjectives, verbs,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="577" width="61">or nouns).</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="620" width="294">By doing so, we collect two seed word lists SSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="350" textpieces="0" top="626" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="381" textpieces="0" top="620" width="55">and SW N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="416" textpieces="0" top="626" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="636" width="359">for each emotion e. This step took less than half an hour</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="652" width="359">manually. Note that it does not require any human judg-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="668" width="351">ments and can be implemented automatically if preferred.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="699" width="359">Collecting Online Documents. We can broaden the cov-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="715" width="359">erage of the keywords by collecting documents containing</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="730" width="359">them. We invoked Twitter search API to query each key-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="746" width="359">word and retrieve up to 100 recent tweets per query. We</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="762" width="168">queried each word in SSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="224" textpieces="3" top="767" width="215">e         and SW N      e       separately, and ob-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="1" top="777" width="187">tained two tweet corpora TSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="241" textpieces="0" top="783" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="273" textpieces="1" top="777" width="56">and TW N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="307" textpieces="0" top="783" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="331" textpieces="0" top="777" width="108">. Obviously, other</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="793" width="359">search services can be employed, too. Given the seed word</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="809" width="359">list, this step can be automated without any human inter-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="824" width="48">vention.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="856" width="359">Creating Feature Extractors. We perform stopword re-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="872" width="188">moval and stemming on TSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="243" textpieces="1" top="877" width="71">e          and T</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="316" textpieces="0" top="869" width="20">W N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="314" textpieces="1" top="877" width="125">e        as in [43]. Our</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="887" width="359">stopword list is based on the SMART system [35], aug-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="903" width="359">mented with domain specic stopwords such as bully,bul-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="919" width="359">lying, bullied, bullies, @USER, ref and some punc-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="1" top="934" width="299">tuations. We then represent each tweet in TSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="353" textpieces="0" top="940" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="381" textpieces="1" top="934" width="36">, TW N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="395" textpieces="0" top="940" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="425" textpieces="0" top="934" width="15">by</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="950" width="359">unigrams and bigrams features. We count the occurrences</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="966" width="248">of each feature collectively within TSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="304" textpieces="1" top="971" width="61">e         or T</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="367" textpieces="0" top="963" width="20">W N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="365" textpieces="1" top="971" width="75">e        and re-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="981" width="359">move features appearing less than ve times. We dene a</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="2" top="997" width="358">vocabulary as the union of seed words in SSY N SW N and</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="3" top="1013" width="239">the remained features in TSY N  TW N.</text>
