2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="259" width="359">We use these 35 vectors as feature extractors. Given a test</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="275" width="359">document we apply the same text processing and represent</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="290" width="353">it as feature vector d. We then compute the inner product</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="643" textpieces="0" top="316" width="23">d v</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="342" width="359">against each of the 35 feature extractors v above and ob-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="358" width="359">tain a 35-dimensional vector x. Clearly, no supervision from</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="374" width="216">human is needed in this step either.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="405" width="359">Building Text Classiers. This is the step where tra-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="421" width="359">ditionally labeled bullying tweets are needed. Instead, we</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="437" width="359">use easy-to-obtain distantly-labeled data. Though our do-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="452" width="359">main is tweets, we train a text classier on Wikipedia pages.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="468" width="359">Wikipedia API supports downloading pages matching a ti-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="484" width="308">tle or category name query. For each word in SSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="758" textpieces="0" top="489" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="13" left="787" textpieces="0" top="483" width="40"> SW N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="807" textpieces="1" top="489" width="27">e      ,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="2" top="499" width="359">we collect the retrieved Wikipedia pages. 2 Each such page</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="515" width="359">is automatically labeled as with emotion e. We therefore</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="531" width="359">automatically constructed a labeled Wikipedia corpus with</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="546" width="62">964 pages.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="578" width="359">We run each Wikipedia page in this corpus through our fea-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="593" width="359">ture extractors to represent the page as a 35-dimensional</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="609" width="359">vector. We train a standard 7-class SVM (note we do not</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="625" width="359">model the other class yet) on the Wikipedia corpus. We</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="641" width="359">compared linear and RBF kernels, tuned SVM regularization</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="656" width="359">parameter C and  in the RBF kernel function (exp( x </text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="3" top="672" width="359">y 2)) in the grid {103, 102, . . . , 103} with 10-fold cross</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="688" width="359">validation. The best model is obtained with RBF kernel,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="703" width="359">C = 1000 and  = 0.1.On the Wikipedia corpus, it achieves</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="719" width="359">a CV error of 15%. Its confusion matrix is shown in Table 1.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="475" textpieces="1" top="755" width="262">3.4  Model Evaluation and Usage</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="774" width="359">To understand the performance of the trained SVM, we com-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="790" width="359">pare it against three baseline methods. Note the comparison</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="805" width="359">is based on the Wikipedia corpus, not the Twitter domain</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="821" width="359">where we have no labeled data. Using the SVM on Twitter</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="837" width="260">will be discussed at the end of this section.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="868" width="194">The three baseline methods are:</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="491" textpieces="1" top="912" width="343">1. SSY N. For test document d, we compute the inner</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="509" textpieces="0" top="927" width="101">product d vSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="585" textpieces="0" top="933" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="618" textpieces="0" top="927" width="216">for each emotion e and predict the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="509" textpieces="0" top="943" width="187">class with the maximum value:</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="604" textpieces="1" top="969" width="79">e= arg max</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="667" textpieces="0" top="980" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="685" textpieces="0" top="969" width="48">d vSY N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="708" textpieces="0" top="975" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="735" textpieces="0" top="969" width="4">.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="509" textpieces="0" top="1000" width="159">Ties are randomly broken.</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="476" textpieces="0" top="1024" width="357">2It is important to note that the nature of the Wikipedia</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1040" width="359">API means that the pages do not necessarily contain the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1053" width="359">query keywords, which enables us to learn something more</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1067" width="146">than keyword matching.</text>
