1 <text font="4" height="12" left="103" textpieces="7" top="226" width="314">pri.       0      0      0     4    23     0      1</text>
1 <text font="4" height="12" left="103" textpieces="7" top="242" width="314">rel.        2      1      0    42     0  198      3</text>
1 <text font="4" height="12" left="103" textpieces="7" top="259" width="314">sad.       4      0      2    14     0     4    82</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="306" width="359">Table 2: Cross validation error of dierent methods</text>
1 <text font="4" height="12" left="118" textpieces="3" top="320" width="285">Fast Training SVM  SSY N   SW N   Majority</text>
1 <text font="4" height="12" left="164" textpieces="3" top="337" width="225">0.15            0.31    0.43      0.42</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="1" top="385" width="343">2. SW N. Same as above but use the WordNet keywords:</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="211" textpieces="1" top="410" width="79">e= arg max</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="275" textpieces="0" top="421" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="293" textpieces="0" top="410" width="43">d vW N</text>
2 <text font="8" height="8" left="316" textpieces="0" top="416" width="5">e</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="338" textpieces="0" top="410" width="4">.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="440" width="325">Both baselines are related to simple keyword matching.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="97" textpieces="0" top="468" width="343">3. Majority. All ve feature extractors make their own</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="484" width="331">predictions as above, and there is a majority vote among</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="499" width="325">the ve for the nal decision. Again, ties are randomly</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="114" textpieces="0" top="515" width="45">broken.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="558" width="359">Table 2 shows the cross validation error of these methods.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="574" width="353">The proposed fast training SVM achieves the lowest error.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="605" width="359">However, the above results were all on the Wikipedia corpus.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="621" width="359">Recall that our test domain is Twitter, for which we do not</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="636" width="359">have labeled data. When a test tweet comes, we rst convert</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="652" width="359">it into the 35-dimensional vector via the feature extractors</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="668" width="359">and apply the trained SVM. We set a threshold  on the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="683" width="359">margin output from SVM, whenever the largest margin is</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="699" width="359">lower than  , we predict it as other. Otherwise, we predict</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="715" width="359">the label with the largest margin. The threshold  is set</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="731" width="359">manually by controlling the positive rate at 5% on a separate</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="746" width="140">random tweet data set.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="1" top="781" width="318">4.  EMOTION IN BULLYING TRACES</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="800" width="359">We apply the SVM to 3,001,427 bullying traces from August</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="816" width="359">5, 2011 to April 12, 2012 (about eight months). Figure 2</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="831" width="359">shows the number of daily bullying traces in each emotion</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="847" width="359">categories. Overall, the number of bullying traces is increas-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="863" width="359">ing because of growing social media usages. All emotion</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="878" width="359">curves have the similar shape but dierent oset (note the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="894" width="359">y-axis is in log scale), indicating that the fraction of dier-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="910" width="359">ent emotions remain stable in the study period. The curves</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="925" width="359">show a weekly (7-day) pattern, which we hypothesize is due</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="941" width="359">to fewer direct interactions among students during the week-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="957" width="359">ends. The few spikes are caused by celebrity events related</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="972" width="359">to bullying which generated a large number of tweets. In</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="988" width="359">what follows, we remove the few spike days since they are</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1004" width="48">outliers.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1035" width="359">We aggregate the counts over the study period for each cat-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1051" width="359">egory and compute their fractions over all bullying traces.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="1067" width="359">Figure 3(a) shows that most (94%) bullying traces are not</text>
=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="385" width="359">Figure 2: The daily counts of bullying traces in dif-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="401" width="359">ferent emotion categories from August 5, 2011 to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="417" width="103">April 12, 2012.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="460" width="359">associated with obvious emotions, which matches our ob-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="475" width="359">servations from manual inspection. Figure 3(b) presents a</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="491" width="359">break down of the 6% emotional bullying traces. Half of</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="507" width="359">them contain fear, followed by sadness, anger and relief.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="522" width="359">Embarrassment, empathy and pride are virtually abscent.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="538" width="359">This also highlights the data skewness issue if the human</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="554" width="304">annotators were to manually label bullying traces.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="512" textpieces="1" top="724" width="344">(a) emotional or not        (b) fraction within emotional</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="512" textpieces="0" top="755" width="280">Figure 3: Fraction of emotion categories</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="800" width="359">Recall that participants in a bullying episode take several</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="816" width="359">well-dened roles. We hypothesize that dierent roles may</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="1" top="831" width="359">express dierent emotions.  We apply author-role classi-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="847" width="359">er [43] to the bullying traces, therefore, each tweet is asso-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="863" width="359">ciated with an author role label by this classier. Figure 4</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="878" width="359">shows the fraction of emotions for each authors role. We</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="894" width="359">assume that authors of one role generate tweets in one emo-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="910" width="359">tion with probability p. The bars show the MLE estimations</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="925" width="359">of p and the error bars indicate the Binomial 95% condence</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="941" width="359">intervals. Compared to other roles, accusers seem to express</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="957" width="359">more fear but less anger. Reporter and victims seem to ex-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="972" width="359">perience more sadness and relief than other roles. However,</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="988" width="359">these observations should be taken with a grain of salt: The</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1004" width="359">emotion in a bullying trace may not be the authors own feel-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1020" width="359">ings. It is possible that the authors sometimes discuss other</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1035" width="359">participants emotions. Our emotion classier is not capable</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1051" width="359">of distinguishing emotions of the author vs. of other people.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="475" textpieces="0" top="1067" width="359">A detailed analysis with deeper natural language processing</text>
=============================== PAGE ===================================
=============================== COL ===================================
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="86" width="359">remains future work. In addition, we have noticed that ac-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="102" width="359">cusers often express fear jokingly (i.e., teasing; see below).</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="118" width="359">For example, @USER lol really?! Im so scared!! I hope I</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="133" width="359">am not verbally beaten. You cyber bully ;), @USER you</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="149" width="359">are such a bully!!!haha &amp; im sooooo scared if him.lol. This</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="165" width="349">might help explain why accusers seems to have more fear.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="498" width="359">Figure 4: The fraction of emotions by authors role.</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="531" width="359">In our previous work, we found that many bullying traces</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="547" width="359">were written jokingly (i.e., teasing ), which may indicate the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="562" width="359">lack of severity of a bullying episode [43]. It is interesting to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="578" width="359">see if there is any dierences in terms of emotion between</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="1" top="594" width="358">teasing and non-teasing bullying traces.  In Figure 5, we</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="609" width="359">observe that teasing bullying traces contain less sadness and</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="625" width="359">relief. This seems reasonable, as in general these emotions</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="641" width="359">are expressed more seriously rather than jokingly. On the</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="657" width="359">other hand, teasing bullying traces contain more fear. We</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="672" width="359">speculate that people may pretend to be afraid of a bully</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="688" width="359">even though in reality they are not. For example,@USER</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="704" width="359">Im so scared haha theres like ten girls then like 30 lads! Im</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="719" width="359">gonna get so bullied#boohoo,@USER eh ya!!!! sometimes</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="735" width="359">i very scared to approach them, like i want to bully them like</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="751" width="138">that LOL HAHAHA..</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="1" top="785" width="163">5.  CONCLUSIONS</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="804" width="359">We identied a wide range of emotions in bullying traces and</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="820" width="359">proposed a fast learning procedure to train a model to auto-</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="835" width="359">matically recognizing them. We applied the trained model</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="851" width="359">to Twitter posts on bullying and report several interesting</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="867" width="359">ndings. We hope this study encourages the community to</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="882" width="359">devote more eort to sentiment analysis on bullying, with</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="898" width="300">the goal of reliably identifying individuals at-risk.</text>
2 <text font="3" height="16" left="81" textpieces="0" top="932" width="140">Acknowledgments</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="951" width="372">We thank Kwang-Sung Jun, Hillary Breidel, and Maria Hughes</text>
2 <text font="4" height="12" left="81" textpieces="0" top="967" width="247">for their help on the data and the paper.</text>
